attributes.Notes: Man made from combination of different objects.
The devil's animals and God's. In the contest between God and the devil, certain animals are made by each.
Creation of monkeys: old woman thrown into fire. In unsuccessful imitation of Christ, the smith throws an old woman into the fire. She becomes a monkey.
Plant receives name because of service to Virgin Mary.
God changes nature of plant to punish wastefulness of man: yeild of plant is decreased.
Why grain grows only at the top of stalk (punishment for men's sinfulness).
Moon stolen and divided into quaters.
Mountains from stones dropped from giant's clothes. He carries the stones in his clothes but loses them as he walks.
Man-hedgehog. Upper half of body like hedgehog.
Roc. A giant bird which carries off men in its claws.
Helpful animal reincarnation of murdered child.
Ant grateful for preventing destruction of nest.
Hero kills horse to feed young ravens.
Duck recovers lost key from sea.
Man carried on goat's horns. (Goat is transformed man.)
Faithful old horse to be abandoned.
Tabu: kissing. Usually causes disenchantment or magic forgetfulness.
Tabu: seeing witch in her true form.
Tabu: speaking while searching for treasure.
Tabu: disclosing source of magic power.
Tabu: making unreasonable requests. Given power of fulfilling all wishes, person oversteps moderation and is punished.
Tabu: using grain to clean child.
Golden finger as sign of opening forbidden chamber.
Hair turns to gold as punishment in forbidden chamber.
Bloody egg as sign of disobedience.
Princess's secret sickness from breaking tabu.
Banishment from heaven for breaking tabu.
Transformation to wood for breaking tabu.
Magic skin makes person appear ugly.
Transformation: man to goat (he-goat, she-goat, kid etc.).
Magic sack contains soldiers which appear when it is struck.
Magic elevator. Stone on which one steps carries one underground.
Magic sight by looking under arm.
Person in magic sleep surrounded by protecting hedge.

Swan Maiden. A swan transforms herself at will into a maiden. She resumes her swan form by putting on her swan coat. (It is difficult to tell in most Swan Maiden tales whether the primary form is swan or maiden: the incident may belong at D161.)
Transformation: wisp of hay to horse.
Transformation: apples to pig bristles (frog legs).
Transformation: iron in axe to silver.
Transformation through thoughtless wish of parent.
Transformation to person of rusty color.
Transformation and disenchantment at will. (See, in general, references throughout D610 — D629, D640 — D659, D670 — D699, nearly all of which motifs involve the idea of voluntary transformation.)
Person restored to human form retains certain animal features.
Disenchantment by cutting off animal's limb.
Disenchantment by maintaining silence for a year or more.
Disenchantment by being wakened from magic sleep by proper agent.
Disenchantment by refusing to eat for three days.
Disenchantment by use of crystal ball.
Disenchantment by throwing golden objects into water.
Disenchantment at midnight after owl hoots three times.
Attendants of disenchanted person automatically disenchanted.
Magic objects possessed by witch, sorcerer or evil dwarf.
Magic object received by apprentice from master.
Magic object taken from dead enemy.
Magic object stolen by owner's fiancée.
Herodias as leader of wild hunt.
Man kicked so hard that he flies through the air and is never seen again.
Person lives without food or drink for a year (or more).
Night spent in tree. Hero goes into tree to spend the night.
Fairyland under hollow knoll. Usually entered under roots of trees.
Underworld people from children which Eve hid from God.
Fairy gift disappears or is turned to something worthless when tabu is broken.
Cup given by fairy not to be broken. Bad luck will follow (Luck of Edenhall).
Dwarfs' gold. Seemingly worthless gift given by dwarfs turns to gold.
Giant drinks up a river (lake, sea).
Giant carries man in his pocket (glove, bosom).
Giant carries man on brim of his hat.
Giants live in castles (raths, duns) (ruins of which may still be seen).
Thumbling hides under thimble in table drawer.
Thumbling hides in a snail shell, in a mouse hole.
Skillful tailor sews bean together after bean has split from laughing.
Subterranean world. (See entire section F80 — F109, Journey to lower world.)
Cave of gold, silver and crystal.
Castle in which inhabitants have been turned to stone.
Cloak made from fur of all animals in realm.
Wagon made from nutshell, drawn by duck.
Devil's coming heralded by piercing whistle.
Devil travels in coach drawn by four blood-red horses, the hoofs of which strike fire from the pavement.
One brother rescues another from ogre.
Woman plans to eat her children.
Cannibal sharpens knife to kill captive.
Task: sewing a shirt from flower petals.
Task: sewing together a broken egg.
Task: sewing together a broken ship.
Task: stacking wood from felled forest in one day.
Task: carrying ever-increasing burden up mountain.
Task: filling twelve bed-ticks with feathers. Done by helpful birds.
Task: building exact replica of castle in wax.
Quest to devil for answer to riddle questions.
Quest for the most beautiful rug.
Quest for the most beautiful ring.
Fear test: going into the church at night and ringing the bell.
Recognition because of imperfection of disguise.
Heat test. Attempt to kill hero by burning him in fire.
Magic manifestation at execution proves innocence.
Recognition by unique ability to perform magic act.
Bride helps suitor perform his tasks.
Recognition by unique manner of playing flute.
Bride chosen from girls assembled at feast.
Princess on the pea. Princess recognized by her inability to sleep on bed which has a pea under its dozen mattresses.
Riddle solved by listening to propounder talk in his sleep.
Woman transformed to flower is recognized by the absence of dew on petals.
Hero takes token from sleeping princess.
Branches broken from tree to prove journey.
Cup taken as proof that one has been present at feast.
Flail substantiates story of witnessing threshing in heaven.
Stolen ring as proof of daring theft.
Inscribed name on article as token of ownership.
Saber with king's name inscribed on it.
Articles of clothing with name embroidered on them taken as tokens.
Ring with names inscribed on it.
Identification by producing three golden apples.
Task assigned before wife may rescue husband from supernatural power.
Tasks performed with help of old woman.
Task performed with aid of magic object.
Rabbit thought to be a cow. Servant sent to bring in cows is found chasing rabbits.
Giant thought to be a hill.
Pious pilgrim dies unknown in his father's house. (Miraculous manifestations.)
Army appears like forest. Surprises enemy. Each soldier carries branches. (Birnam wood comes to Dunsinane.)
Enemy induced to give up siege by pretending to have plenty of food.
Animal substituted for child served at meal.
Choice among several gifts. The worst horse, armor, or the like proves best.
Adventures from pursuing enchanted animal (hind, boar, bird). (Guiding Beast.)
Suttee. Wife burned with dead king.
Brave soldier and timid cabinet-maker as companions.
Punishment: millstone dropped on guilty person.
Punishment: trampling (kicking) to death by horses.
Covering with honey and exposing to flies.
Child cast out because of his stupidity.
Abandoned wife hidden under a tub.
Couvade. Father goes into confinement at time of childbirth.
